We're thrilled to officially release "We Believe," a music video about the Roland-Story Community School District!

Created as part of our 50th anniversary celebrations, the video speaks to how the district's core values drive our efforts to ensure all students learn and thrive.

Featured in the video are Roland-Story alumni Ethan Beck ('18), Addisen Popp ('20), Lars Skaar ('99), Megan McGuigan ('20), and Matthew Mehrtens ('20).

As we start a new school year, we are proud to share this great video. "We Believe" celebrates all we have accomplished as a school district in our first 50 years, and it generates excitement for what's ahead in our next 50!

https://vimeo.com/440490560/3744456df0

post_text:
The Roland-Story Community School District plans to welcome students back into our buildings for in-person instruction starting Monday, August 24. However, we will also offer a remote learning option for families who request it.

To access the request form for this option, visit https://bit.ly/RSRemoteRequest. We ask that you complete the form and submit it to the district’s central office at 1009 Story Street in Story City, or email it to Amy Trask at atrask@roland-story.k12.ia.us.

Our principals and teachers are working hard to determine what remote learning will look like this fall. We are committed to providing a high-quality educational experience for students who will be learning from a distance.

We look forward to the start of the 2020-2021 school year!

post_text:
We know there's a lot of anxiety about the start of the school year. We feel it too. Please know that we are relying on guidance from our state and county health departments and closely monitoring what happens with local COVID cases. The situation could change significantly, one way or another, in the next few weeks.

Our Return-to-Learn Plan will be released publicly next week. This plan will provide some valuable information, but it will NOT indicate which learning model (On-Site, Remote, or Hybrid) we will be in when school starts on August 24th. We will make that decision closer to the start of the school year based on the best available health and safety data at that time.

We continue to plan for a variety of scenarios. We encourage all Roland-Story families to do the same. Any decisions we make will be with the health and safety of our students, staff, and families as our top priority. Thanks for your continued patience and support.

While we do not yet know exactly what school will look like this fall, please know that Roland-Story will be prepared for all possibilities.

post_text:
The Iowa Department of Human Services will distribute additional food assistance benefits to families throughout the state, including here at Roland-Story.

The Families First CoronaVirus Act allows states to issue benefits to households with children in prekindergarten through 12th grade that lost access to free and reduced-price school meals due to extended school closures last spring.

Eligible families will receive $307.80 per child. If your household received food assistance benefits in April, May or June, you will see that amount added to your EBT card by July 15. If you have not received food benefits in the past three months, you will get a P-EBT card in the mail before July 21.

The P-EBT cards will come in a white envelope addressed with your child's name, with a return address from Austin, TX. The cards themselves will be white with black font, with "IOWA P-EBT" printed at the top. Once you receive your card, follow the included instructions to activate it.

Learn more: https://dhs.iowa.gov/P-EBT

post_text:
Earlier today, Governor Reynolds announced that summer sports may begin practices on June 1.

After this announcement, the Iowa Department of Education, in consultation with the Iowa Department of Public Health, the Iowa High School Athletic Association, and the Iowa Girls High School Athletic Union, provided school districts with guidance regarding the rules and restrictions that will apply to summer sports. We are now reviewing that guidance and will communicate with our student-athletes and families once we have made some key decisions on next steps.

Above all else, the safety of our student-athletes is our top priority. In the meantime, we want to thank everyone for their continued patience. We will follow up soon with more information.

post_text:
Happy Teacher Appreciation Week! For several years now it has been a tradition for Roland-Story school board members to hand-deliver apples to each staff member as part of this annual recognition during the first week of May. This small gesture of gratitude for what our staff do to support students and families is something the board looks forward to each year. Since delivering apples in-person is really not an option this year, the board created this short video to express their heart-felt appreciation for all that our staff do to serve others.

Please join us this week in thanking our staff for making Roland-Story Schools a great place to learn and grow. #NorseProud

post_text:
Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, Roland-Story High School has rescheduled our graduation ceremony to Sunday, June 28, 2020 at 2:00 p.m.

While we hope to hold a traditional in-person graduation, we do not yet know if that will be possible. If not, we will hold a virtual event. This would not be an ideal solution, but it would give a chance to celebrate the Class of 2020 in spite of the unfortunate circumstances. We will share more information as soon as we can.

Prom has been canceled for this year.

We know these decisions will cause a great deal of disappointment for our students and families. The situation surrounding COVID-19 has been especially difficult for our seniors, who were looking forward to taking part in spring sports and activities, attending prom, and finishing out the school year strong. Please know that we share in your disappointment.

Thank you to the entire Roland-Story community for your patience and understanding over the past several weeks. It has been wonderful to see so many people step up and offer their support during this incredibly challenging time.

April 15 at 8:25 AM ·

#norsenation, in partnership with the City of Story City and Roland, Roland-Story will be taking part in #LightUpIA this Friday and next Friday starting at 8:00 pm at our football, baseball, and softball facilities. post_text:
Dear Parents,
As students will be doing more learning and reading from home, there are abundant helpful resources for parents and students through your local Area Education Agency (AEA). Iowa’s AEAs provide a broad variety of digital content for students, teachers and families selected by Iowa educators. Students and teachers are familiar with these vetted, age-appropriate, and high-quality digital resources and use them in their daily work. These resources can be found on the AEA website: https://www.heartlandaea.org/library-and-digital-resources/online-resources.

These resources include read-aloud ebooks, ebooks, digital audiobooks, videos, encyclopedias, articles, newspapers and more for our youngest and oldest learners. Many of these things do not require usernames and passwords, but a few still do. If your student can’t remember their login information, please reach out to your child’s teacher or librarian to get a reminder. Thanks.

If your student can’t remember their login information, please reach out to your child’s teacher or librarian to get a reminder. Thanks.

Online Resources | Heartland Area Education Agency
Online databases are excellent resources for reports, references and fun! They are an extension to the materials available at your school library. The databases are purchased by the AEA and require a username and password assigned to your school.

As we conclude spring break, Roland-Story teachers are excited to re-engage with students and parents.

While we will not be implementing full-scale e-learning during the next three weeks, we do want our students to stay sharp and active. Beginning this week, teachers will be reaching out to students and families sharing educational resources and checking in to see how everyone is doing. Please be looking for these efforts to connect.

We understand that this may be a difficult time for our students and their families. We are here if you need us. Please stay healthy and safe!

post_text:
Update on COVID-19 (March 15, 2020)
Tonight, Governor Reynolds announced that she is recommending Iowa schools close for four weeks to mitigate the spread of COVID-19. This recommendation comes as a result of guidance from the Iowa Department of Public Health and based on CDC guidelines. Tomorrow (March 16) Governor Reynolds will hold a press conference that will more clearly outline school closure expectations. We will provide additional information as it becomes available.

The Roland-Story Community School District is on a scheduled Spring Break this upcoming week, March 16-20. This allows us some time to make appropriate decisions and communicate details. Thanks for your patience and understanding in these unprecedented circumstances.

post_text: Mr. Schlatter, Emily Berggren, Matthew Mehrtens, and Amy Rathmacher attended today's Story County Philanthropy Luncheon and accepted the Outstanding Youth Group in Philanthropy Award on behalf of our high school. Emily spoke to those in attendance and had this to say, "Our district core values include humbly serving others, making people the priority, and being leaders with character. We want to make sure that these are not just words that we say, but that we choose to live them out each day not only as individuals, but as a district." A huge congratulations and thank you to all of our student organizations and their advisors for creating opportunities for our students to learn, grow, and give. #norseproud

post_text: Happy Veterans Day! On Monday the middle school students showed their gratitude for the men and women who have served our country. Our students did a wonderful job singing, playing instruments, reading poems, and reading essays. Roland Story Middle School would like to thank all of our veterans for everything they have done to make this the most amazing country in the world! Thank you for all the freedoms that we get to enjoy each and every day. We are GRATEFUL! We also want to thank the Roland American Legion Post #307 for their generous donation of $600 to RSMS! We appreciate the partnership we have with this group as well as the Story City American Legion as well as the Auxiliary. Thanks for all you do!

Brandon Hansen, Key Coop Agronomist and Sara Clausen, Key Coop Communications Director, stopped by RSMS today to present the check to Mr. Town. The new freezer will allow us to order more frozen meat for our food pantry that will get us through each month until the next delivery. We are GRATEFUL for Key Coop and Land O Lakes for this awesome grant!

Congratulations to the Roland-Story high school vocalists that were selected to the Iowa All-State Chorus this past weekend! Last year a record 15 Roland-Story students qualified for this honor. This year, in competition between all schools, no matter district size, the chorus students again broke the school record having 18 students selected to the Iowa All-State Chorus! We are so proud of all the students who tried out. Results by district are below:
Johnston - 21
Roland-Story - 18
Ankeny - 17
West Des Moines, Valley - 17
Dowling Catholic - 12
Indianola - 8
Urbandale - 7
Ames - 4
Ankeny Centennial - 3
Gilbert - 1
Saydel - 1
Nevada - 0

post_text: As part of our 50th anniversary celebrations, we're inviting all 10 state championship teams to special events throughout the school year. We recently honored the back-to-back state championship football teams (1980 & 1981) with a dinner, recognition during a game, and a state champions t-shirt. It was great to see everyone reunite, reminisce, and share stories! Thank you to all the players and coaches involved in these football championships for leaving Roland-Story with a legacy of excellence on and off the field. Also, a special thanks to our Norsemen sponsors and organizers who made this memorable event possible! Go Norse! #NorsemenAt50

post_text: At Roland-Story, this is another example of who we are. The High School FFA is wrapping up another successful harvest in our community garden. Students have donated more than 29,000 pounds of fresh produce to four local food pantries this season. When Sam Skaar was asked about giving up part of his summer break to work in the garden, he said, "Some things are just a little bigger than you are." Thanks to Sam, his fellow FFA members, and Mr. Taylor for their dedication to our communities! #HumblyServingOthers

post_text: Did you know that because of our partnership with DMACC the class of 2019 earned 1191 college credits during their junior and senior years at Roland-Story? That's an average of 12 credits per student and equates to more than $200,000 in tuition savings for these students and their families. These credits were earned through online courses, concurrent-enrollment classes taught by Roland-Story teachers, and classes taken at the DMACC campus in Ames.
text: Did you know that because of our partnership with DMACC the class of 2019 earned 1191 college credits during their junior and senior years at Roland-Story? That's an average of 12 credits per student and equates to more than $200,000 in tuition savings for these students and their families. These credits were earned through online courses, concurrent-enrollment classes taught by Roland-Story teachers, and classes taken at the DMACC campus in Ames.

post_text: Step inside the No Screen Zone at Roland-Story Preschool! In recent years, we've seen plenty of research showing the negative impacts of too much screen time at a young age. In our preschool program, we engage our students without technology. Watch this video and see how their imaginations come alive! post_text:
The Roland-Story PTO’s Step It Up Fitness fundraiser was a big success! We are pleased to announce that $48,852 was raised to support academic and co-curricular programs at the elementary and middle schools.

While we are thrilled with the success of this fundraiser, the district and PTO acknowledge that we learned a few things through this experience. We could have done a better job communicating with students and families in advance of the fundraiser, and some have shared that the timing was not ideal. We agree. We are sorry for any confusion or inconvenience that may have happened this time around. We will learn from this experience and communicate better next time.

The Roland-Story Community School District applauds our PTO for their efforts to think outside the box with this fundraiser. We appreciate all they do to support our students and staff — and a special thank you to all who contributed to the Step It Up Fitness fundraiser this year!

Learn more about the PTO: https://www.rolandstorypto.org/

post_text:
Roland-Story High School earned fourth place honors in the prestigious 2017-2018 Bank Iowa Traveling Challenge Cup competition. The Traveling Challenge Cup is a program designed to recognize Iowa High School students for academic excellence in the classroom and outstanding achievement during state athletic and fine arts competitions.

The Bank Iowa Traveling Challenge Cup is a combined, statewide, year-long competition among all member high schools of the IHSAA, IHSSA, IGHSAU and IHSMA.

Any event that is sanctioned by the IHSAA, IHSSA, IGHSAU and IHSMA is eligible to be included. Points are awarded to the schools based on their participation for a state championship in athletics, music, speech, debate and each individual teams academic accomplishments in the classroom whether they make it to a state tournament or not.

Learn more and check out the full results here: http://oakenenterprises.com/traveling_challenge_cup/2017-18/standings.cfm?Cup_Class=2A&order=tsp

post_text: Congratulations to the high school Physics Team (Onyx) for their first place finish at the Regional Physics Competition last week hosted by the Science Center of Iowa. Team Onyx advances to state competition at UNI's McLeod Center on Tuesday, April 10th. Twelve teams from central Iowa competed in: toothpick bridge building, mousetrap car, challenge problem, soda straw arm, and catapult. Roland-Story brought three teams to the competition; Onyx, Crimson, Valhalla. All three teams performed well. Good luck at state team Onyx!

JOIN US on Thursday, March 22nd at 6:00 p.m. at the high school for an informative evening on a variety of current mental health topics impacting youth and adults. Brian Carico, a passionate supporter of students who struggle both academically and emotionally, will be our keynote speaker.

Booths open at 6:00 p.m. Keynote is on depression and suicide.
Breakout session topics include; cyber bulling, anxiety, ADHD, depression, self-injurious behaviors, eating disorders, whole-brain child, and trauma.

shared_text:
Roland-Story Middle School
March 2, 2018 at 9:18 AM ·

The Emmy Award-winning Saturday morning educational cartoon series and pop culture phenomenon is now the basis for one of the most fun musicals ever to hit the stage, Schoolhouse Rock Live! JR. This loose, revue-like structure follows Tom, a young schoolteacher, who is nervous about his first day of teaching. He tries to relax by watching television, when various characters representing facets of his personality emerge from the set and show him how to win his students over with imagination and music. Memorable songs as “Just a Bill,” “Great American Melting Pot” and “Conjunction Junction” bring his lesson plans vividly to life. The Roland-Story eighth grade choir invites you to their production of this fast-paced musical on Thursday, March 8, at 7:00 pm. Admission is $5 for adults (students/children are free).

post_text: Congratulations to Roland-Story High School students, Maddie Urbanek and Taryn Perry for being selected as finalists in the 2018 National Merit Scholarship Program! This program started with approximately 1.5 million entries, and has now been narrowed to 15,000 finalists. Madeleine and Taryn represent the top 1% of high school students! #NorseProud

post_text:
The Roland-Story High School academic competition team the Schol-R-S sent a team to the Iowa Science Bowl on Saturday hosted at Iowa State University. Students included captain Taryn Perry, Eli Ruben, Kat Hawley, Tristan Balmer, and alternate Sam Sirna. This was the 28th Science Bowl in the state, and the event is sponsored by the US Department of Energy. The winner of the state contest advances to the National Science Bowl competition in April; Johnston High School won this year's event. Teams come from all corners of the state, with small schools competing against the largest in the state. In the morning Round Robin tournament, RS faced Des Moines Central, Carroll, Liberty, and Greene County.

In addition to the Iowa Science Bowl, the Schol-R-S sent two teams to the Iowa Knowledge Bowl last fall at DMACC in Ankeny. This spring, a team will compete in the ISU Virtual Quiz Bowl. The Schol-R-S started three years ago as part of Eli Ruben's project for the Extended Learning Program at RSHS.
